Here's my reasoning and the resulting OpenAPI 2.0 Response Object for the GET /api/v1/comments endpoint:

- The index method in App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\CommentController returns a paginated collection of CommentResource items. This means the API response will be a paginated JSON structure containing:
  - data: an array of comment resource objects
  - links: a set of pagination links (first, last, prev, next)
  - meta: pagination metadata (current_page, from, last_page, path, per_page, to, total)

- The fields of each CommentResource item are defined in app/Http/Resources/Comment.php:
  - id
  - content
  - posted_at (ISO8601 string)
  - humanized_posted_at (string)
  - author_id
  - post_id
  - author_name
  - author_url
  - can_delete (boolean)

- The types for these fields are inferred from PHP types and typical JSON conversions:
  - id, author_id, post_id, current_page, from, last_page, per_page, to, total are integers
  - content, posted_at, humanized_posted_at, author_name, author_url are strings
  - can_delete is boolean
  - posted_at uses date-time format

- The final response structure does not include any references ($ref) and is self-contained, inline with Swagger 2.0 expectations for a paginated collection.

